Kyle Terada/USA TODAY SportsThis season will undoubtedly be a head-scratcher for Kobe Bryant and the Lakers. Having started 1-7, the Los Angeles Lakers are staring at the prospect of their worst season since moving to L.A. five-plus decades ago. But there could be a reward to their patience in next May's NBA draft lottery. Every non-playoff team has incentive to lose as many games as possible to improve its draft pick, but the Lakers' stakes are even higher. Because of their ill-fated trade for Steve Nash, the Lakers owe the Phoenix Suns their first-round pick -- if it falls outside the top five selections in the 2015 draft. The Lakers keep their pick if it lands in the top five, a prospect that looks increasingly likely. To read more of Kevin Pelton's column on whether the Lakers will be bad enough to keep their 2015 top-five-protected draft pick, become an Insider today. Insider Become an insider and get access to all our articles and tools. Subscribe Sign in View Insider Benefits Â» Magazine subscribers: activate your Insider account. Recommend0 Tweet0 Email Subscribe Kevin Pelton Follow Archive Co-author, Pro Basketball Prospectus series Formerly a consultant with the Indiana Pacers Developed WARP rating and SCHOENE system